# ADR-0015 — Company Brain Architecture

- Status: Accepted
- Date: 2026-07-19
- Deciders: Pharos Architecture Team

---

# Context

Pharos AI Operating System is designed to assist a real company.

The platform requires a permanent source of organizational truth.

Examples include:

- company structure
- engineering standards
- architectural decisions
- products
- services
- business processes
- legal policies
- operational procedures
- historical decisions

This information must exist independently from:

- Runtime
- Agents
- Memory
- LLM providers

A dedicated architecture is required.

---

# Decision

The Company Brain is the authoritative representation of the organization.

It acts as the canonical source of organizational knowledge.

```
                Company Brain
                       │
                       ▼
             Knowledge Providers
                       │
                       ▼
                  AI Agents
                       │
                       ▼
                 RuntimeIntent
                       │
                       ▼
                    Runtime
```

The Company Brain never performs execution.

The Company Brain never performs reasoning.

It stores truth.

---

# Purpose

The Company Brain represents the organization itself.

It answers questions such as:

- What products exist?
- How is the engineering department organized?
- Which architectural decisions have been accepted?
- What are the company standards?
- How should releases be performed?
- Which domains belong to the company?
- Which policies are active?

---

# Responsibilities

The Company Brain owns:

- company documentation
- ADRs
- engineering standards
- operational standards
- product documentation
- organizational structure
- departments
- employee roles
- company policies
- company history
- company assets

The Company Brain does not own:

- conversations
- prompts
- execution
- planning
- reasoning
- temporary state

---

# Relationship to Runtime

Runtime never accesses Company Brain directly.

Runtime receives RuntimeIntent only.

The Runtime remains company-independent.

The same Runtime should be usable by any organization.

---

# Relationship to Agents

Agents retrieve organizational information through
Knowledge Providers.

Agents interpret Company Brain.

Agents never modify Company Brain during execution.

---

# Relationship to Knowledge

Knowledge Providers expose Company Brain.

The Company Brain is the source.

Knowledge Providers are retrieval mechanisms.

Examples:

```
Markdown Provider

↓

Company Brain
```

```
Git Provider

↓

Company Brain
```

```
Vector Provider

↓

Company Brain
```

Changing providers never changes Company Brain.

---

# Relationship to Memory

Memory represents experience.

Company Brain represents organizational truth.

Examples:

Memory:

- user prefers concise responses
- previous conversation
- completed workflow
- temporary project context

Company Brain:

- engineering standards
- architecture
- policies
- products
- company structure

Memory is dynamic.

Company Brain changes intentionally through governance.

---

# Governance

Changes to Company Brain are deliberate.

Examples include:

- approving an ADR
- publishing a new engineering standard
- updating product documentation
- changing company policies

Routine AI execution must not mutate Company Brain.

---

# Architectural Principles

## Single Source of Truth

Every organizational fact exists in one canonical place.

---

## Runtime Independence

Runtime never embeds company knowledge.

---

## AI Independence

Company Brain exists independently from any AI model.

LLMs may consume Company Brain.

They never become the source of truth.

---

## Technology Independence

The Company Brain is independent from storage technology.

Possible implementations include:

- Markdown
- Git
- Database
- Object Storage
- Hybrid systems

Architecture remains unchanged.

---

# Dependency Rules

Company Brain depends on nothing.

Knowledge Providers depend on Company Brain.

Agents depend on Knowledge Providers.

Runtime depends on neither.

Tools never modify Company Brain directly.

Memory never replaces Company Brain.

---

# Alternatives Considered

## Embed company knowledge into prompts

Rejected.

Knowledge becomes duplicated,
difficult to maintain,
and impossible to govern.

---

## Store company knowledge in Memory

Rejected.

Memory is contextual.

Company Brain is authoritative.

---

## Runtime reads Company Brain

Rejected.

Execution should remain independent from organizational knowledge.

---

# Consequences

Positive:

- single organizational truth
- deterministic Runtime
- reusable AI infrastructure
- replaceable LLM providers
- governed documentation
- easier auditing
- scalable knowledge management

Negative:

- additional architectural subsystem
- governance process required

The benefits significantly outweigh the operational cost.

---

# Future Evolution

Future Company Brain capabilities may include:

- semantic indexing
- graph relationships
- version history
- document ownership
- approval workflows
- automated consistency checks
- organizational analytics
- AI-assisted documentation

None of these require changes to Runtime.

